40|$|One of the {{fundamental}} proportions in social reproduction is that ratio between <b>production</b> <b>of</b> <b>means</b> <b>of</b> <b>production</b> and <b>of</b> consumer goods under which high rates <b>of</b> growth <b>of</b> <b>production</b> are combined with the fuller satisfaction of the material and cultural needs of the population. Inasmuch as this relationship must be dynamically planned, its planning {{comes down to the}} establishment of the rates of growth of both subdivisions <b>of</b> social <b>production</b> and, consequently, <b>of</b> the ratio between these rates <b>of</b> growth. Moreover, <b>production</b> <b>of</b> <b>means</b> <b>of</b> <b>production</b> and <b>of</b> consumer goods must be considered on a national economic scale. In reality, however, judging by the published data, the relationship between the rates <b>of</b> growth <b>of</b> <b>production</b> <b>of</b> <b>means</b> <b>of</b> <b>production</b> and <b>of</b> consumer goods is established in our country in planned fashion only with respect to industrial production. And the very division <b>of</b> social <b>production</b> into two subdivisions (<b>means</b> <b>of</b> <b>production</b> â Group A, and consumer goods â Group B) is applied, in the published statistical materials, exclusively with respect to industry. ...|$|R
